title: Panthers aim to defend TVL tourney title
text: Panthers aim to defend TVL tourney title Published: Wednesday, October 14, 2015 5:15 PM CDT Four state-ranked volleyball teams will be among the 13 Twin Valley League squads that will play Saturday for the conference tournament championship.League champion Centralia is the three-time defending league tournament champion. The Panthers are ranked No. 2 in 1A Division I where Hanover was No. 7 in the Kansas Volleyball Association’s poll.Axtell comes into the league tournament with the No. 2 ranking in 1A Division II.In 2A is Washington County at No. 7. “This year the league is top heavy and maybe not quite as tough one through 12, but still very tough,” said Centralia coach Kimbrook Tennal. “We have not been really on all year, but if we do get on this weekend then we will be awfully tough to beat. Should be some great volleyball.”The tournament starts at 9 a.m. at Washington.“I think this year’s tournament is completely up in the air,” said Valley Heights coach Jenny Yungeberg. “I think there are several teams that could win the tourney.”League play ended Tuesday with Centralia sweeping host Washington County, 25-21, 25-20, and Doniphan West, 25-4, 25-15.At Valley Heights, the Mustangs won against Hanover, 25-14, 10-25, 26-24, and fell to Linn, 16-25, 25-19, 17-25. Hanover defeated Linn, 25-23, 23-25, 25-13.Axtell tied Centralia at 11-1 with wins at Wetmore. The Eagles won against WHS 25-12, 25-15, and over Blue Valley, 25-16, 25-16. Though AHS had the same record as Centralia, the Eagles will finish second. Earlier this season AHS lost to the Panthers. Host Frankfort won over Troy, 25-19, 25-11, and downed Onaga, 25-3, 25-15. In tournament play Saturday at the Marysville Invitational, Hanover went 4-0 in pool play and 1-1 in bracket play to take third in the 10-team tournament.The Wildcats in 1A Division I defeated 3A Royal Valley, 25-21, 20-25, 25-20, in the consolation match. In the semifinal round, Hanover fell to Concordia, 16-25, 23-25.In pool play, Hanover opened the invitational with a 25-21, 25-17 win against 2A Valley Heights. The Cats defeated Royal Valley, 25-20, 25-22; 2A Republic County, 22-25, 25-17, 25-16; and 2A Washington County, 25-19, 15-25, 29-27.Heights was 0-4 in the tournament. The Mustangs lost to Republic County, 17-25, 16-25; Royal Valley, 24-26, 20-25; and Washington County, 14-25, 27-25, 18-25.
